==Latin==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|la|itc-pro|*ad}}, from {{der|la|ine-pro|*ád||near, at}}. Cognates include English {{m|en|at|}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Classical}} {{IPA|/ad/|lang=la}}
* {{audio|la-cls-ad.ogg|Audio (Classical)|lang=la}}

===Preposition===
{{head|la|preposition|+ accusative}}

# {{label|la|direction}} [[toward]], [[to]], [[on]], [[up to]], [[for]]
#* {{Q|la|Lucretius|De rerum natura|4|quote=Fugere '''ad''' puppim colles campique videntur.|trans=The hills and fields appear to fly '''toward''' the ship.}}
#* {{Q|la|Pliny the Elder|Naturalis Historia|2|quote=Meridie umbrae cadunt '''ad''' septentrionem, ortu vero '''ad''' occasum.|trans=At noon the shadows fall '''towards''' the north, [and] at sunrise, point '''to''' the west.}}
#* {{Q|la|Virgil|Aeneid|1|93|quote=Duplices tendens '''ad''' sidera palmas.|trans=Stretching both hands '''to''' the stars.}}
#: {{ux|la|'''Ad''' vim atque '''ad''' arma confugere.|t=To fly '''to''' violence and '''to''' fighting.}}
#: {{ux|la|'''Ad''' maiorem Dei gloriam.|t='''For''' the greater glory of God.}}

====Related terms====
* [[ad-]] (same word modified and used as a prefix)

====Usage notes====
* The word '''ad''' is an [[antithesis]] to {{m|la|ab}} (just as {{m|la|in}} is to {{m|la|ex}}; in a progressive order of relation, {{m|la|ad}} denotes, first, the direction toward an object; then the reaching of or attaining to it; and finally, the being at or near it.)
* Often used of geographical position of a place in reference to the points of compass, with the verbs {{m|la|iaceō||lie, be situated}}, {{m|la|vergō||incline, slope}}, {{m|la|spectō||observe, see}} etc.:
*: ''Asia iacet '''ad''' meridiem et austrum, Europa '''ad''' septentriones et aquilonem.''
*:: Asia lies '''near''' the prime meridian and the south, Europe '''near''' the northern regions and northern wind. (There are two words for north.)
*: '''''Ad''' Atticam vergente.''
*:: Inclining '''to''' Attic.
* When appended to the beginning of a word, ''ad'' often becomes {{m|la|ap-}} when followed by ‘p’, as in {{m|la|appretiō}}, from {{m|la|pretium}}. But note that {{m|la|adpretiō}} is also found.

